196
00:14:30,320 --> 00:14:41,060
Given the situation we're in now and wanting to extract energy from vacuum — energy we can use to power lamps, motors, supply houses — we need to

197
00:14:41,060 --> 00:14:48,300
find a reaction that can give us a substantial amount of electromagnetic energy from vacuum.

198
00:14:48,880 --> 00:14:57,340
Until 1957 we didn't know for sure about the existence of such a reaction that would be widely accessible.

199
00:14:58,780 --> 00:15:02,800
But from 1957 this became known.

200
00:15:03,320 --> 00:15:06,940
Then the phenomenon of so-called broken symmetry was discovered.

201
00:15:07,160 --> 00:15:17,320
Lee and Yang put forward the hypothesis of its existence in 1956, in the beginning of 1957, in the first half of 1957.

202
00:15:18,180 --> 00:15:21,940
This is very short time for a work to gain world fame.

203
00:15:22,140 --> 00:15:26,320
Publications appeared predicting the discovery of broken symmetry.

204
00:15:26,860 --> 00:15:32,180
We're talking about broken symmetry of the flow of virtual particles in vacuum.

205
00:15:32,180 --> 00:15:35,640
This means that one part of it isn't similar to the other.

206
00:15:36,040 --> 00:15:37,520
Some changes happened in it.

207
00:15:38,580 --> 00:15:40,700
This is what's called broken symmetry.

208
00:15:41,080 --> 00:15:46,400
Moreover, this change should be substantial enough to be observable.

209
00:15:46,680 --> 00:15:53,320
As Lee said when he encountered broken symmetry, something virtual became accessible for observation.

210
00:15:54,040 --> 00:15:57,400
Thus, now we have something measurable, at least theoretically.

211
00:15:57,940 --> 00:16:00,880
Something big enough to be noticed and measured.

212
00:16:00,880 --> 00:16:09,080
Broken symmetry became the magical tool whose existence was proven in 1956-57.

213
00:16:09,800 --> 00:16:16,080
But this hypothesis was so important that it could revolutionize science if proven experimentally.

214
00:16:16,340 --> 00:16:21,740
A very strong experimental physicist immediately joined them, to prove whether it was true or not.

215
00:16:21,980 --> 00:16:26,220
This was so important that everything had to be done very fast, and they succeeded.

216
00:16:26,220 --> 00:16:30,360
In fact, in February 1957 Wu and her colleagues...

217
00:16:30,360 --> 00:16:37,080
Wu recently died... proved it experimentally, in very short time after the hypothesis was put forward.

218
00:16:39,440 --> 00:16:48,540
The influence and consequences of this discovery on physics as a whole were so significant that the Nobel Prize was also awarded unprecedentedly fast.

219
00:16:51,200 --> 00:16:55,500
Lee and Yang received it the same year, in December 1957.

220
00:16:55,500 --> 00:17:02,300
I want to give a full picture of how fast the revolution in science happened and how fast recognition came.

221
00:17:06,460 --> 00:17:16,900
One of the phenomena of broken symmetry — one of those things that transform part of virtual energy into positive or observable energy that can be fixed and measured — was

222
00:17:16,900 --> 00:17:20,340
broken symmetry of opposite charges.

223
00:17:20,520 --> 00:17:21,820
Let's talk about charge.

224
00:17:23,880 --> 00:17:26,820
Charge is a very unusual thing.

225
00:17:27,700 --> 00:17:31,820
We have no absolutely accurate definition of the concept of "charge."

226
00:17:32,700 --> 00:17:42,660
This still isn't a clear concept, but nevertheless we have a series of facts about it, some of which formed back in the 19th century.

227
00:17:44,380 --> 00:17:53,160
Elementary particle physics in the 20th century allowed us to learn much about how charge behaves, how it works and interacts with other things.

228
00:17:54,060 --> 00:17:59,300
If I have a charge in the classical understanding, then this'll be one electron at rest in space.

229
00:18:00,180 --> 00:18:05,320
It's actually not at rest in empty space, as we usually picture, going from the classical concept.

230
00:18:05,880 --> 00:18:11,820
It's located as if in a boiling pot — in a flow of particles that chaotically move and collide with each other.

231
00:18:12,440 --> 00:18:17,880
Very small, tiny photons are absorbed and dropped again, and all that.

232
00:18:17,880 --> 00:18:25,020
Each time the electron absorbs a photon, a tiny increment of its mass is observed, and so on.

233
00:18:25,720 --> 00:18:29,720
This is a boiling pot, and the charge itself is very dynamic.

234
00:18:30,780 --> 00:18:45,060
Essentially, if I place this charge in such a pot, in the empty space we'd better call vacuum, say this electron, a negative charge.

235
00:18:45,520 --> 00:18:49,740
Around it the bubbles with opposite charges will dominate.

236
00:18:49,760 --> 00:18:55,440
That is, here we'll have many positive charges appearing and disappearing at huge speed.

237
00:18:56,000 --> 00:18:57,880
Incredible speed.

238
00:18:59,860 --> 00:19:07,360
If we have opposite charges, then we have what's called force lines in classical physics.

239
00:19:08,700 --> 00:19:09,860
But this isn't yet force.

240
00:19:09,860 --> 00:19:15,820
We have lines of attraction between these opposite charges.

241
00:19:17,840 --> 00:19:31,560
What we have now is broken symmetry of opposite charges, because in the middle there's one charge, and around it a whole screen of bubbles with opposite charges.

