712
00:54:37,100 --> 00:54:38,300
The load stays the same.

713
00:54:38,540 --> 00:54:40,140
The load is connected in series.

714
00:54:40,440 --> 00:54:41,260
Of course, no problem.

715
00:54:41,480 --> 00:54:41,760
Good.

716
00:54:41,760 --> 00:54:50,700
If you, of course, aren't going to power the load with negative energy, you need to develop a load that can be powered by negative energy, and then the load will not only power itself, but also

717
00:54:50,700 --> 00:54:52,740
give you energy from vacuum.

718
00:54:52,840 --> 00:54:54,420
Use the current, or what?

719
00:54:54,620 --> 00:54:55,420
Positive energy.

720
00:54:55,680 --> 00:54:57,000
Right, positive energy.

721
00:54:57,180 --> 00:55:00,100
Then a load is a load, and impedance is impedance.

722
00:55:00,400 --> 00:55:00,540
Yes.

723
00:55:00,820 --> 00:55:03,940
Why does it happen that we still need to power the load?

724
00:55:04,140 --> 00:55:04,760
It's all current.

725
00:55:04,960 --> 00:55:06,700
And we still need to return the current back.

726
00:55:07,260 --> 00:55:07,540
No.

727
00:55:09,540 --> 00:55:09,980
Good.

728
00:55:09,980 --> 00:55:13,300
The only way to return current is to use it again.

729
00:55:13,460 --> 00:55:16,160
By the way, let's talk about current.

730
00:55:16,500 --> 00:55:18,960
Current isn't at all like water flow in a pipe.

731
00:55:19,600 --> 00:55:20,420
It's all not so.

732
00:55:20,980 --> 00:55:25,200
Electrons in wires are free — they constantly jump into other atoms, jump back and forth.

733
00:55:25,400 --> 00:55:27,260
This is called the Drude electron gas.

734
00:55:28,220 --> 00:55:32,900
Drude discovered it around 1900.

735
00:55:33,380 --> 00:55:39,920
In a conductor at every moment we have an electron gas consisting of jumping electrons.

736
00:55:40,760 --> 00:55:47,380
And when we send this energy flow along the conductor, this flow passes through all these charges.

737
00:55:47,820 --> 00:55:49,760
It moves almost at the speed of light.

738
00:55:50,460 --> 00:56:00,660
If everything was ideal, it would move at the speed of light — but we have inductance, capacitance, and so on, so its speed is less than light, with which real potential and real

739
00:56:00,660 --> 00:56:02,080
energy flow along the conductor.

740
00:56:02,700 --> 00:56:04,460
The electron itself doesn't move that way — only on average.

741
00:56:04,460 --> 00:56:08,640
In a circuit the electron moves along the conductor at about 10 centimeters per hour.

742
00:56:09,020 --> 00:56:09,980
Per hour!

743
00:56:10,560 --> 00:56:15,980
About 10 centimeters along the conductor because it has to jump, and we have electron drift.

744
00:56:16,520 --> 00:56:19,420
On average it shifts, jumps, then shifts further.

745
00:56:20,720 --> 00:56:25,120
This is drift statistics formed by electrons.

746
00:56:26,240 --> 00:56:32,940
The electron can't simply move along the conductor because the electrons ahead prevent this, throwing it back.

747
00:56:33,720 --> 00:56:36,060
Everything should be in interaction.

748
00:56:36,800 --> 00:56:41,780
Jumps, collisions, and drift along the conductor at about 10 centimeters per hour.

749
00:56:43,260 --> 00:56:46,960
This is the actual electron speed in longitudinal movement in the conductor.

750
00:56:47,620 --> 00:56:50,400
Meanwhile the energy moves practically at the speed of light.

751
00:56:51,040 --> 00:56:54,080
Thus, one of the ways to go from this...

752
00:56:54,080 --> 00:56:56,000
Say you have a good copper conductor.

753
00:56:57,960 --> 00:57:05,720
The reaction of electrons to current after voltage transfer in it is so fast we can consider it instantaneous.

754
00:57:06,520 --> 00:57:11,500
Different people cite different data, but it's about 10 to the minus 16 seconds.

755
00:57:12,040 --> 00:57:13,080
This is very short time.

756
00:57:13,480 --> 00:57:18,600
Forget about measuring the distance between when you apply voltage and current starts to flow.

757
00:57:19,040 --> 00:57:20,140
That is, effectively.

758
00:57:20,360 --> 00:57:27,820
In normal circuits we assemble with copper wires and the like, current starts flowing immediately after we apply voltage.

759
00:57:28,160 --> 00:57:30,220
And the dipole is always destroyed.

760
00:57:30,220 --> 00:57:31,940
Here's voltage, here's current.

761
00:57:31,960 --> 00:57:34,540
But suppose we slowed the process.

762
00:57:34,940 --> 00:57:37,820
We briefly froze the electron, literally for a millisecond.

763
00:57:38,120 --> 00:57:39,240
A thousandth of a second.

764
00:57:40,740 --> 00:57:44,540
This is a pretty long time for something moving at the speed of light.

765
00:57:47,480 --> 00:57:49,680
300 million meters per second.

766
00:57:49,720 --> 00:57:57,260
And you delayed the start of movement by 300 thousand meters — understand — that could pass before electron movement starts.

767
00:57:59,340 --> 00:58:02,620
Simply delaying them for one millisecond.

768
00:58:02,720 --> 00:58:10,000
It would create potential in the whole scheme with a very small, near-zero current.

769
00:58:10,660 --> 00:58:16,700
If you assemble a device that automatically provides this delay in the conductor, this can be done.

770
00:58:19,300 --> 00:58:26,980
If you make a conductor from an aluminum alloy with 2% iron content, you can get a current delay of about one millisecond.

771
00:58:30,380 --> 00:58:38,660
You can calculate everything and measure the iron percentage, and all that, to get a delay of one millisecond.

772
00:58:40,120 --> 00:58:41,120
We need an alloy.

773
00:58:41,360 --> 00:58:44,060
We need a good alloy so nothing prevents the particles.

774
00:58:46,840 --> 00:58:51,540
If we have a good alloy with 2% iron, take a small content.

775
00:58:51,540 --> 00:59:03,120
We can make a conductor with a delay of approximately one millisecond between when voltage is applied — even if you applied it very sharply — and when any significant current

776
00:59:03,120 --> 00:59:04,020
starts flowing.

777
00:59:04,140 --> 00:59:06,180
The delay is about one millisecond.

778
00:59:06,600 --> 00:59:24,200
During this millisecond, if your circuit is no longer than 300 thousand meters or 300 kilometers — because no one uses circuits of such length — you can create potential in the circuit without help of current,

779
00:59:24,460 --> 00:59:26,240
electric energy, or work.

780
00:59:27,600 --> 00:59:28,720
Energy is free.

781
00:59:29,240 --> 00:59:30,700
Potential energy is free.

782
00:59:30,960 --> 00:59:31,900
It doesn't cost a penny.

783
00:59:32,080 --> 00:59:36,800
It comes from vacuum thanks to dipole formation, and remains with you for free.

784
00:59:36,800 --> 00:59:41,460
You only have to pay when you need to do work on dissipating energy and changing its form.

785
00:59:41,820 --> 00:59:47,960
We'd want to create potential in this circuit, and then disconnect the generator from it before current flows.

786
00:59:47,960 --> 00:59:49,280
We can do this.

787
00:59:49,500 --> 00:59:51,400
It's simpler than simple.

788
00:59:54,180 --> 00:59:58,500
You just need to find a metallurgical lab that would make this conductor.

789
00:59:58,820 --> 01:00:02,440
